@node overview "EASys!, ©'1998 by Thomas Neidhardt: FileManager..."
@prev main

   @{" < " link main} @{b}EASys! Wizards@{ub}

        ©'98 Thomas Neidhardt, 91058 Erlangen, GERMANY
____________________________________________________________________


   @{b}Comfortable File-Management@{ub}

   managing files and drawers (best started by function-Key,
   RShift-F5 proposed) everytime and everywhere just on the
   fingertip:

   @{" + " SYSTEM "run <>NIL: ${RefTable/File-Manager}"} The EASys! FileManager: @{i}${RefTable/File-Manager}@{ui}



   @{b}For comfortably ...@{ub}

   @{b}copying files and drawers@{ub}, including a fully informational
   security-request before overwriting files. This is still
   a unique feature for the AMIGA! @{i}${RefTable/File-CopyServer}@{ui}

   @{b}moving files and drawers@{ub}, dito. @{i}${RefTable/File-MoveServer}@{ui}

   @{b}renaming files and drawers@{ub}
   @{i}${RefTable/File-RenameServer}@{ui}  now supporting Wildcard
   rename operations for renaming whole directorie's files from one
   name pattern to another, (case sensitive renaming!) i.e.:

   *.jpeg   ->  *.jpg
   Bild*    ->  Picture*
   *alles*  ->  *all*


   @{b}trashing files and drawers@{ub}, including choice if the
   passed data should be moved to the TrashCan or
   just should be deleted or the action should be cancelled.
   System-Wide overall partitions with one TrashCan!

   If the famous GlobalTrash (available from Aminet) is
   installed and running on your system, it will be used
   in place of the standard Workbench-Trashcan SYS:TrashCan/

   @{" + " SYSTEM "run <>NIL: ${RefTable/File-Trash}"} The EASys! TrashManager: @{i}${RefTable/File-Trash}@{ui}


   @{b}printing files of various types simply by dropping@{ub} them onto
   a ToolManager button and completing a little Dialog.
   @{i}${RefTable/Print-Manager}@{ui}

   @{b}viewing information about Libraries/Binaries and other Files@{ub}
   (name, version, size, File-Comments -> editable,
   Documentation or File-Monitor may be called directly)
   @{i}${RefTable/File-Info-Server}@{ui}


____________________________________________________________________
@endnode



@node GUI "EASys!, ©'1998 by Thomas Neidhardt: FM GUI..."
@prev EASys!.guide/main

   @{" < " link main} @{b}EASys! Wizards@{ub}

        ©'98 Thomas Neidhardt, 91058 Erlangen, GERMANY
____________________________________________________________________



   @{b}FileManager:   Short help for the filemanager GUI{ub}


   @{b}The File-Requester@{ub}, showing up when calling the EASys!-FileManager
   is thought for entering/selecting the Files you would like to
   process. Multi-Selection is possible by simultaneously pressing
   the left Shift-Key and the left Mouse-Button, activating/selecting
   List-entries (the Files). The offered functions will supply
   the following basic File-operations:

    >    Copy the selected files/directories to ...
         A Path-Selection Requester will then show up in order to
         select the destination directory for the copying-operation.
         New destination-dirs may be created there by simply
         entering a new path to an existing destination-path.
         Overwriting of duplicate files will be recognized. If so,
         you will be shown complete Information, concerning source and
         destination, giving you the choice of continuing or not.

    >>   Move ...  (further: see Copy)

   Single Files as well as destination-dirs may also be set by Drag&Drop
   of Workbench-Icons into the File-Requester's windows.




   @{b}The buttons ...@{ub}

   del  Delete the selected files. A security request will ask you
        if you would to delete the files totally or, if you would like
        to have them moved to a Trash-Directory, assigned by "Muell:"
        (english: Trash = german: Muell).

   Ren  Rename ... for each selected file, a rename-Request will
        be shown. You may also rename by pattern, (case sensitive renaming!)
        e.g.:

        *.jpeg   ->  *.jpg
        Bild*    ->  Picture*
        *alles*  ->  *all*


    i   Show a complete File-Information (including Version, Date, ...)
        Supplying further functions.

   ed   start your Text-Editor with the selected Files

   01   start the File Monitor ..

    !   StartFile (Send to..) will show a big selection-list for
        further operations and applications to process/view your
        selected Files.

    ?   will call this online documentation

   stop Stops the FileManager


____________________________________________________________________
@endnode


@node args "EASys!, ©'1998 by Thomas Neidhardt: FM commandline..."
@prev EASys!.guide/main

   @{" < " link main} @{b}EASys! Wizards@{ub}

        ©'98 Thomas Neidhardt, 91058 Erlangen, GERMANY
____________________________________________________________________



   @{b}Arguments@{ub}

   ${RefTable/File-Manager} is based upon the Rexx-Script
   EASys!_rexx:FileManager.rexx - and may also be called by specific
   arguments and thus offers direct access to several functions. This
   will give you the possibility to build-in some additional functio-
   nality directly into workbench operations (as suggested by the
   included ToolManager/RekeyIt configuration):

   Using Arguments:        EASys! RefTable-Call by:

       -CopyF              ${RefTable/File-CopyServer}
       -MoveF              ${RefTable/File-MoveServer}
       -Ren_F              ${RefTable/File-RenameServer}
       -InfoF              ${RefTable/File-Info-Server}
       -Fnote              ${RefTable/File-Note}
       -SavAs              ${RefTable/File-SaveAs}
       -MovAs              ${RefTable/File-MoveAs}
       -fLink              ${RefTable/File-ScriptLink}
       -sProg              ${RefTable/File-LaunchProg}

   at least one more argument must be given (a File or Directory).
   This may be done by passing it by Shell arguments as well as
   by dropping Files to a ToolManager Dock or selecting a
   Workbench Icon and then choosing the
   appropriate ToolManager Menu.


   Using  @{i}${RefTable/File-Manager} -DIR SYS:System @{ui}  will enable
   you, to start the Filemanager using SYS:System (as an example)
   as source path.

____________________________________________________________________
@endnode

